*Injecting Spring Security beans as method parameters

  OfficeFloor registers every bean in the Spring application context as a managed object available by
  type.  Spring Security beans — including <<<UserDetailsService>>>, <<<PasswordEncoder>>>, and the
  <<<SecurityFilterChain>>> itself — are therefore available as plain parameters with no annotation:

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/security/bean.GET.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestsecurity/SecurityBeanService.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  This is the same mechanism used for any Spring <<<@Service>>> or <<<@Component>>> — there is no
  special handling for security beans.



*Method-level security — <<<@PreAuthorize>>>

  <<<@PreAuthorize>>> on a service method is evaluated by OfficeFloor before the method is invoked.
  The full Spring Security SpEL expression language is available — <<<hasRole()>>>,
  <<<hasAuthority()>>>, <<<isAuthenticated()>>>, and any custom expressions configured via a
  custom <<<MethodSecurityExpressionHandler>>>:

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/security/preauthorize.GET.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestsecurity/PreAuthorizeService.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  If the expression evaluates to false, OfficeFloor returns <<<403 Forbidden>>> before the service
  method body executes.



*Method-level security — <<<@Secured>>>

  <<<@Secured>>> accepts one or more role names (including the <<<ROLE_>>> prefix).  Enable it in
  the security configuration with <<<securedEnabled = true>>>:

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/security/secured.GET.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestsecurity/SecuredService.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}



*Method-level security — <<<@RolesAllowed>>>

  The JSR-250 <<<@RolesAllowed>>> annotation works the same way.  Enable it with
